The OLS solutions is given by \beta_1 = 0.7847 and \beta_2 = 0.2046. The RSS at this point is 37.8592.


The LASSO Solution
If we decide to apply Lasso, with a constraint of \left|\beta_1\right| + \left|\beta_2\right| \leq 0.5 (this is equivalent to using \lambda = 0.311), the OLS solution would not be a valid solution because 0.7847 + 0.2046 = 0.9893\geq 0.5. The only solutions that would be acceptable would be the ones that lie within the square shown in the figure below.





The LASSO method then needs to shrink the coefficients until they are in the square. So, the LASSO solution is the best solution in the feasible region (the square).





As we can see from the figure above, the LASSO solution was in a vertice of the square, where one of the coefficients is zero. This is not unusual. The LASSO solution will generally be in a vertice, where one or more of the coefficients are zero. For this reason, LASSO is also considered a variable selection method. The LASSO coefficients, in this case, were \beta_1 = 0.5 and \beta_2=0.
We could also look at this on the perspective of the loss function LASSO(\bm\beta, \lambda). Naturally, this function is a function of \lambda. The figure below shows the loss function for different values of \lambda.




// Create a Meshgrid for plotting
values_plot = {
    let b1 = Array(100).fill().map((element, index) =&gt; -4 + index*0.08);
    let b2 = Array(100).fill().map((element, index) =&gt; -4 + index*0.08);


    let rss = [];
    for (let i = 0; i &lt; b1.length; i++) { 
        rss[i] = [];
        for (let j = 0; j &lt; b2.length; j++) { 
            rss[i].push(cancer_data.map(elem =&gt; (elem[0] - b1[i] * elem[1] - b2[j] * elem[2]) ** 2 + lambda * (Math.abs(b1[i]) + Math.abs(b2[j])) ).reduce((a, t) =&gt; a + t, 0));
        }
    };

    return {
        b1: b1,
        b2: b2,
        rss: rss
    };
};







